The expectation of the minimum eigenvalue of the adjacency matrix of a graph can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
e_{\min }^{\alpha }(\boldsymbol{A}) = \frac{1}{\alpha } \sum\limits_{i=1}^{n} \min \left\{ \left\vert a_{i,i+1} \right\vert, \alpha \right\} ,
\label{eq:min_eigenvalue}
\end{equation}%
where $\alpha \geq 0$ is a tuning parameter and $\boldsymbol{a} = (a_{ij})_{n \times n}$ is the matrix of weights of the graph. If $\alpha = 0$, the expectation is equal to the minimum of the absolute values of the weights, while if $\alpha > 0 $ the expectation takes into account also the direction of the edges. The critical value for the tuning paramter $\alpha$ is given by $\alpha _{c} = \left( n-1 \right) / 2$.
